Is the 1971 cherokee dataset significant from the 2001 cherokee dataset?

t.test(cherokee$VOT ~ cherokee$year, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  cherokee$VOT by cherokee$year
## t = 2.6116, df = 42, p-value = 0.01245
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   6.555374 51.136934
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 1971 mean in group 2001 
##          113.50000           84.65385

The null hypothesis is that the difference between the 1971 cherokee dataset mean and the 2001 cherokee dataset mean is 0. The alternative hypothesis is that the difference between the means is not 0.

At 95% confidence, we reject the null hypothesis. The difference between the 1971 cherokee dataset mean and the 2001 cherokee dataset mean is not 0. Therefore, these two datasets are significant from each other.

Do the VOT measurements fall in an approximately normal distribution?

t.test(cherokee$VOT ~ cherokee$year)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  cherokee$VOT by cherokee$year
## t = 2.6137, df = 36.825, p-value = 0.0129
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   6.480602 51.211706
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 1971 mean in group 2001 
##          113.50000           84.65385
ggplot(cherokee1971, aes(VOT))+geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)

qqnorm(cherokee1971$VOT)
qqline(cherokee1971$VOT)

The graph and histogram appear to have a approximately normal distribution for the 1971 cherokee dataset.

ggplot(cherokee2001, aes(VOT))+geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)

qqnorm(cherokee2001$VOT)
qqline(cherokee2001$VOT)

The graph and histogram appear to be skewed right for the 2001 cherokee dataset. Therefore, to confirm our conclusion, we will use the two sample Wilcoxson rank-sum test.

wilcox.test(VOT~year, cherokee)
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(x = c(67L, 127L, 79L, 150L, 53L, 65L, 75L, :
## cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  VOT by year
## W = 346.5, p-value = 0.007492
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

The two datasets appear to come from two different spreads. This result is consistent with the t-test results, which explains why the two datasets are significant and have different median values. The VOT varies significantly based on year.

More R visualization

eng = english
ggplot(eng, aes(RTnaming))+geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

qqnorm(eng$RTnaming)
qqline(eng$RTnaming)

The histogram shows a bimodal distribution. I believe it appears to be bimodal based on the fact of the two separate groups that may affect the distribution - young v.s. old participants. This can explain why the distribution is split in 2; one reflects the young participants’ reaction time, the other would reflect the old participants’ reaction time.

ggplot(eng, aes(Familiarity))+geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

This histogram appears to be normally distributed. This suggests that the average subjective rating of words appears to be around 3, and the data comes from an approximately normally distributed population.

ggplot(eng[eng$AgeSubject == 'young',], aes(RTnaming, Familiarity)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

There appears to be a negative correlation between the familiarity of the word and the word-naming reaction time. As young people’s familiarity with the word decreases, the reaction time in naming it increases. This makes sense, as it would take longer to recognize unfamiliar words.
